<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871117-0101 </DOCNO><HL> Security Federal Sandamp;LCleared for ConversionTo Captial Stock Thrift</HL><DD> 11/17/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK) </IN><DATELINE> CLEVELAND  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Security Federal Savings andamp; Loan Association said the Federal Home Loan Bank Board approved a plan to convert Security from a federal mutual savings and loan to a federal capital stock thrift.    The plan provides for the sale of 589,375 shares of common stock of Security for $10 a share, based on an independent appraisal of the estimated market value of Security upon conversion.    As a mutual, the company is owned by its depositers. As a stock savings bank, Security will be owned by its shareholders.    The thrift said a subscription offering of the stock is being made to depositors, borrowers, directors, officers and employees of Security. Concurrently, unsubscribed shares are being offered to the general public with preference to individuals residing in the counties in which Security has offices. The subscription offering will terminate Dec. 7 at noon EST; the direct community offering will terminate Dec. 21 at noon EST. </TEXT></DOC>